Joe Morris, Aidan Cremins, Amrit Sandhu, Mark Moreno, Ben Kanarick¶

Read in data and clean the text column, filter out weekend podcasts, update dates¶

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# read in data
df = pd.read_json('wallstreet-breakfast.json')

# clean up data
df = df.rename(columns={0: 'date', 1: 'text'})

df['text'] = df['text'].astype(str)

df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])
df[['date', 'time']] = df['date'].astype(str).str.split(' ', expand=True)

df['text'] = df['text'].astype(str).str.replace('\[\"', '')
df['text'] = df['text'].astype(str).str.replace('\"\]', '')
df['text'] = df['text'].astype(str).str.replace('\[\'', '')
df['text'] = df['text'].astype(str).str.replace('\'\]', '')

# filter out weekend podcasts
df = df[~df['text'].str.lower().str.contains('weekend bite')]
df = df[~df['text'].str.lower().str.contains('welcome to the weekend')]
df = df[~df['text'].str.lower().str.contains('welcome to weekend')]
df = df[~df['text'].str.lower().str.contains('week\'s episode')]
df = df[~df['text'].str.lower().str.contains('this is we can buy')]
df = df[~df['text'].str.lower().str.contains('we can bite')]
df = df[~df['text'].str.lower().str.contains('today is thursday, october 20th')]

# filter out 'editor roundtable' podcasts
df['editors_roundtable'] = df['text'].str.lower().str.contains('editors roundtable')

# make two dataframes for each type of podcast
editor_df = df[df['editors_roundtable'] == True]
df = df[df['editors_roundtable'] == False]

# array of months full name
months = ['January', 'February', 'March', 'April', 'May', 'June', 'July', 'August', 'September', 'October', 'November', 'December']
# phrases and date dictionary
date_phrases = {'may the fourth' : '05-04'}


# Find month and day within text and make sure it's a month and day
df['extracted_date'] = df['text'].str.extract(r'(\w{3,9} \d{1,2})')
df['extracted_date'] = df['extracted_date'].where(df['extracted_date'].str.contains('|'.join(months)), np.nan)

# change string pulled out to a date object
df['extracted_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['extracted_date'], format='%B %d')

# change to date in date_phrases dictionary if it exists and change to date object
for phrase, date in date_phrases.items():
    df['extracted_date'] = df['extracted_date'].where(~df['text'].str.lower().str.contains(phrase), pd.to_datetime(date, format='%m-%d'))

# change date to datetime object
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])

# make a new column of month and day of extracted_date and year of date
df['new_date'] = df['date'].dt.strftime('%Y') + '-' + df['extracted_date'].dt.strftime('%m-%d')

# change new_date to datetime object
df['new_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['new_date'])

# set date column to new_date
df['date'] = df['new_date']

# if date in the future, then change date year to previous year
df['date'] = df['date'].where(df['date'] < pd.to_datetime('today'), df['date'] - pd.DateOffset(years=1))

# drop extracted_date, new_date, time, editors_roundtable columns
df = df.drop(columns=['extracted_date', 'new_date', 'time', 'editors_roundtable'])

Get word frequencies and clean the text¶

In [3]:
# get word frequency for each word in text without stopwords
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from nltk.probability import FreqDist

stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

df['clean_text'] = df['text'].astype(str)

df['clean_text'] = df['clean_text'].str.lower()
df['clean_text'] = df['clean_text'].str.replace('[^\w\s]','')
df['clean_text'] = df['clean_text'].str.replace('\d+', '')
df['clean_text'] = df['clean_text'].str.replace('http\S+|www.\S+', '', case=False)
df['clean_text'] = df['clean_text'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in x.split() if word not in (stop_words)]))

word_freq = pd.Series(' '.join(df['clean_text']).split()).value_counts()

Find sectors mentioned by finding corresponding sector for each company¶

In [7]:
# adds a column listing sectors based on companies mentioned
df['sectors'] = df['companies_list'].apply(lambda x: list(data[data['Company Name'].isin(x)]['Sector']))

# a column for each sector and put percent each sector is mentioned in the podcast
for sector in data['Sector'].unique():
    df[sector] = df['sectors'].apply(lambda x: round((x.count(sector) / len(x)), 4) if len(x) > 0 else 0)

# make abreviation for each sector
sector_abrev = {'Consumer Discretionary': 'CD', 'Consumer Staples': 'CS', 'Energy': 'E', \
    'Financials': 'F', 'Health Care': 'HC', 'Industrials': 'I', 'Information Technology': 'IT', 'Materials': 'M', \
        'Real Estate': 'RE', 'Telecommunication Services': 'TS', 'Utilities': 'U', 'Communication Services': 'CSS'}

# make a dictionary of companies and their sectors
company_sector = {}
for company in data['Company Name'].unique():
    company_sector[company] = sector_abrev[str(data[(data['Company Name'] == company)]['Sector'].iloc[0])]

# replace company names with sector names in text using dictionary
df['sector_text'] = df['text'].copy()
for company, sector in company_sector.items():
    df['sector_text'] = df['sector_text'].apply(lambda x : x.replace(company, sector).replace(company.title(), sector))

Function to find sentiment of sentences related to each sector¶

In [8]:
import nltk
from nltk.tokenize import sent_tokenize
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from nltk.tag import pos_tag
from nltk.sentiment.vader import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer


def get_sentiment(text, searchs):

    returns = []

    for search in searchs :
        # tokenize text into sentences
        sentences = sent_tokenize(text)

        # tokenize each sentence into words
        tokenized_sentences = [word_tokenize(sentence) for sentence in sentences]

        # get sentences that contain the search word
        sentences = [sentence for sentence in tokenized_sentences if search in [word for word in sentence]]

        # get sentiment of each sentence
        for sentence in sentences:
            sentence = ' '.join(sentence).replace(' ,', ',').replace(' .', '.').replace(' ?', '?').replace(' !', '!').replace(' :', ':').replace(' ;', ';').replace(' %', '%').replace(' \'', '\'').replace('$ ', '$').replace(' & ', '&')

            # initialize sentiment analyzer
            sid = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

            returns.append([sentence, sid.polarity_scores(sentence)['compound']])

    # get average sentiment of sentences
    try :
        avg_sentiment = sum([x[1] for x in returns]) / len(returns)
    except :
        avg_sentiment = 0

    return returns, avg_sentiment

# get first row text to test function
text = df['sector_text'][0]

# check if working using text above
get_sentiment(text, ['CSS'] )

ETF data for getting returns of the sectors¶

In [9]:
# get index prices for each sector using yahoo finance
import yfinance as yf

# get dictionary of sectors and etfs for each sector using vanguard etf for each sector
sector_tickers = {'Communication Services' : 'VOX', 'Consumer Discretionary' : 'VCR', 'Consumer Staples' : 'VDC', 'Energy' : 'VDE', 'Financials' : 'VFH', 'Health Care' : 'VHT', 'Industrials' : 'VIS', 'Information Technology' : 'VGT', 'Materials' : 'VAW', 'Real Estate' : 'VNQ', 'Utilities' : 'VPU'}

# get index prices for each sector and store in a dictionary
sector_prices = {}
for sector, ticker in sector_tickers.items():
    sector_prices[sector] = yf.download(ticker, start='2021-10-01', end='2022-10-15')
    # add a column for returns (open - close / open)
    sector_prices[sector]['change'] = (sector_prices[sector]['Close'] - sector_prices[sector]['Open']) / sector_prices[sector]['Open']

# if sector sentiment for sector is less than 0, then set sector weight to negative sentiment, else keep sector weight the same
for sector in sector_prices.keys():
    df[sector] = df.apply(lambda x: -x[sector] if sector in x['sentiment'] and x['sentiment'][sector] < 0 else x[sector], axis=1)

Get returns for each sector per date and get our strategy return¶

In [12]:
# get return of each sector for each date
for sector, prices in sector_prices.items():
    df[sector + ' return'] = df['date'].apply(lambda x: prices[prices.index == x]['change'].values[0] if x in prices.index else 0)

# get return of our strategy by multiplying sector weights by sector returns
df['total return'] = df.apply(lambda x: sum([x[sector + ' return'] * x[sector] for sector in x['sentiment'].keys()]), axis=1)
